## SQL: Data Cleaning
  
The main goals are to **standardize text**, **fix prices**, **ensure referential integrity**, and **validate discount ranges**, following common cleaning patterns in SQL projects.

```sql
-- 1. Standardize customer names and city casing
UPDATE customers
SET name = INITCAP(TRIM(name)),
    city = INITCAP(TRIM(city));

-- 2. Remove customers with NULL key fields
DELETE FROM customers
WHERE name IS NULL
   OR city IS NULL;

-- 3. Fix invalid product prices (null or <= 0)
WITH median_price AS (
    SELECT category,
           PERCENTILE_CONT(0.5) WITHIN GROUP (ORDER BY unit_price) AS med_price
    FROM products
    GROUP BY category
)
UPDATE products p
SET unit_price = m.med_price
FROM median_price m
WHERE p.category = m.category
  AND (p.unit_price IS NULL OR p.unit_price <= 0);

-- 4. Remove sales rows with invalid foreign keys
DELETE FROM sales s
WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM customers c WHERE c.customer_id = s.customer_id)
   OR NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM products p WHERE p.product_id = s.product_id)
   OR NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM stores st WHERE st.store_id = s.store_id)
   OR NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM calendar cal WHERE cal.date = s.date);

-- 5. Ensure discount is between 0 and 0.8
UPDATE sales
SET discount = CASE
                 WHEN discount < 0   THEN 0
                 WHEN discount > 0.8 THEN 0.8
                 ELSE discount
               END;
```

> Note: You may need to adjust functions like `INITCAP` or `PERCENTILE_CONT` depending on your database (e.g., MySQL vs PostgreSQL).

