## SQL: Analysis & Business Questions

The core business logic, inspired by typical sales‑analytics questions in portfolio projects.

### 1. Top 10 Products by Revenue and Quantity

```sql
WITH sales_enriched AS (
    SELECT s.sale_id,
           s.product_id,
           s.quantity,
           s.discount,
           (s.quantity * p.unit_price * (1 - s.discount)) AS revenue
    FROM sales s
    JOIN products p ON s.product_id = p.product_id
)
SELECT p.product_id,
       p.product_name,
       p.category,
       SUM(se.quantity)          AS total_quantity,
       ROUND(SUM(se.revenue), 2) AS total_revenue
FROM sales_enriched se
JOIN products p ON se.product_id = p.product_id
GROUP BY p.product_id, p.product_name, p.category
ORDER BY total_revenue DESC, total_quantity DESC
LIMIT 10;
```

**What it answers:**  
- Which products generate the most revenue?  
- Which products have the highest volume sold?  
This is useful for merchandising and inventory decisions.

---

### 2. Average Order Value per Customer

```sql
WITH sales_with_revenue AS (
    SELECT s.sale_id,
           s.customer_id,
           (s.quantity * p.unit_price * (1 - s.discount)) AS revenue
    FROM sales s
    JOIN products p ON s.product_id = p.product_id
)
SELECT c.customer_id,
       c.name,
       ROUND(SUM(swr.revenue) / COUNT(DISTINCT swr.sale_id), 2) AS avg_order_value
FROM sales_with_revenue swr
JOIN customers c ON c.customer_id = swr.customer_id
GROUP BY c.customer_id, c.name
ORDER BY avg_order_value DESC;
```

**What it answers:**  
- How much does each customer spend on average per order?  
- Who are the highest value customers?

This is a common metric for customer segmentation and marketing.
