### 3. Effect of Discount on Quantity Sold

```sql
WITH sales_buckets AS (
    SELECT CASE
             WHEN discount = 0 THEN '0%'
             WHEN discount > 0 AND discount <= 0.05 THEN '0-5%'
             WHEN discount > 0.05 AND discount <= 0.10 THEN '5-10%'
             WHEN discount > 0.10 AND discount <= 0.20 THEN '10-20%'
             WHEN discount > 0.20 AND discount <= 0.30 THEN '20-30%'
             ELSE '>30%'
           END AS discount_bucket,
           quantity
    FROM sales
)
SELECT discount_bucket,
       COUNT(*)                AS num_sales,
       ROUND(AVG(quantity), 2) AS avg_quantity_per_sale
FROM sales_buckets
GROUP BY discount_bucket
ORDER BY discount_bucket;
```

**What it answers:**  
- As discounts increase, does average quantity per sale also increase?  
- Which discount range drives the highest volume?

This gives a first indication of discount effectiveness without building a full statistical model.[web:27][web:34][web:35]

